            <h1>Support good cops who can't speak</h1>
            <p class="usa-intro">The eye of justice are blind, but not everyone has a voice.</p>
            
            <!-- Share everything -->
            <h2 id="share-everything">Share the good and bad</h2>
            <p>It is important to not only share the stories of negative interactions, but also those that are positive. Ensuring those that set a good example are promoted through the ranks is how those same individuals will serve as role models for others, while also ensuring they are protected from potential retaliation. In those situations where an officer (or officers, including those who simply stand by and watch) does wrong, make sure you record the interaction. While the <a href="https://www.aclu.org/issues/criminal-law-reform/reforming-police/aclu-apps-record-police-conduct" alt="" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ACLU has made an app for some states</a>, with <a href="https://www.nolo.com/legal-encyclopedia/recording-the-police-legal.html" alt="" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NOLO making a guide for others</a>.
            <p>Whether you submit something through an online form or with a hard copy in the mail, save a copy of your submission and consider <a href="https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/investigations/2019/04/24/biggest-collection-police-accountability-records-ever-assembled/2299127002/" alt="" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">sharing it with the public</a>. USA Today collected the largest group of misconduct records</a> ever assembled, finding 30,000+ that were banned, but even more that were disciplined but able to continue working in another jurisdiction.</p>
            <p>Unfortunately, it is often only when a story is picked up by the media that something will happen. We need to change that. Reinforce the values and culture of our communities through constant communication with our local governments.</p>
