            <!-- Why this matters -->
            <h2 id="why-this-matters">Why should this matter to you?</h2>
            <p>There are <a href="https://project.wnyc.org/disciplinary-records/" alt="WNYC's analysis on public records law applicability to police disciplinary records." alt="" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">only 12 states in the entire country</a> that make police disciplinary records generally available to the public. This is a double-edged sword, meaning many of the cops who are complimented by their community won't be heard from as well, leaving examples of good cops to the whims of the city or department's social media team.</p>
            <p>Making sure the general public knows which cops are good and which ones aren't will ensure that the practice of moving one town over to continue a career never happens again, while also promoting a practice of promoting those who truly serve the community from within.</p>
